Implementing a simple user input form using basic UI elements involves several steps. Here's a step-by-step guide to create a basic form using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript:

**HTML Structure**

Create an HTML file (`index.html`) with the following structure:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>User Input Form</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
</head>
<body>
    <h1>User Input Form</h1>
    <form id="user-form">
        <label for="name">Name:</label>
        <input type="text" id="name" name="name"><br><br>
        <label for="email">Email:</label>
        <input type="email" id="email" name="email"><br><br>
        <label for="message">Message:</label>
        <textarea id="message" name="message"></textarea><br><br>
        <button type="submit">Submit</button>
    </form>
    <div id="result"></div>

    <script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```
**CSS Styling**

Create a CSS file (`styles.css`) to add basic styling to the form:
```css
body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
}

#user-form {
    width: 50%;
    margin: 40px auto;
    padding: 20px;
    border: 1px solid #ccc;
    border-radius: 10px;
    box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
}

label {
    display: block;
    margin-bottom: 10px;
}

input, textarea {
    width: 100%;
    padding: 10px;
    margin-bottom: 20px;
    border: 1px solid #ccc;
    border-radius: 5px;
}

button[type="submit"] {
    background-color: #4CAF50;
    color: #fff;
    padding: 10px 20px;
    border: none;
    border-radius: 5px;
    cursor: pointer;
}

button[type="submit"]:hover {
    background-color: #3e8e41;
}
```
**JavaScript Interactivity**

Create a JavaScript file (`script.js`) to add interactivity to the form:
```javascript
const form = document.getElementById('user-form');
const resultDiv = document.getElementById('result');

form.addEventListener('submit', (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();

    const name = document.getElementById('name').value;
    const email = document.getElementById('email').value;
    const message = document.getElementById('message').value;

    if (name && email && message) {
        const result = `Name: ${name}\nEmail: ${email}\nMessage: ${message}`;
        resultDiv.innerText = result;
    } else {
        alert('Please fill out all fields!');
    }
});
```
**Explanation**

1. We create an HTML form with basic UI elements (labels, input fields, textarea, and a submit button).
2. We add CSS styling to make the form look visually appealing.
3. We add JavaScript code to listen for the form submission event.
4. When the form is submitted, we prevent the default form submission behavior using `e.preventDefault()`.
5. We retrieve the values of the input fields and textarea using `document.getElementById()`.
6. We check if all fields are filled out. If not, we display an alert message.
7. If all fields are filled out, we create a result string with the user input values and display it in a `div` element.

**Example Use Case**

Open the `index.html` file in a web browser and fill out the form. When you submit the form, the result will be displayed below the form.
